1
00:01:12,760 --> 00:01:14,480
I'll take you somewhere later.

2
00:01:14,480 --> 00:01:15,280
Where to?

3
00:01:15,800 --> 00:01:16,920
You'll know when we get there.

4
00:01:16,920 --> 00:01:18,640
It's prepared just for you.

5
00:01:18,880 --> 00:01:19,810
Prepared for me?

6
00:01:20,960 --> 00:01:21,600
Here.

7
00:01:22,600 --> 00:01:23,600
Let's go. Come on.

8
00:01:24,960 --> 00:01:25,880
Yaoyao.

9
00:01:25,880 --> 00:01:27,880
The car you hailed is too luxurious.

10
00:01:28,680 --> 00:01:29,440
Get in.

11
00:01:35,640 --> 00:01:37,900
Hello, last digits of your phone number?

12
00:01:40,280 --> 00:01:41,080
What?

13
00:01:42,039 --> 00:01:42,840
Nothing.

14
00:01:43,520 --> 00:01:44,759
Come, buckle up.

15
00:01:45,920 --> 00:01:47,160
Hey, sir.

16
00:01:47,160 --> 00:01:48,520
This is so luxurious.

17
00:01:48,520 --> 00:01:50,200
Driving such a nice car for Didi.

18
00:01:50,200 --> 00:01:51,000
It's alright.

19
00:01:54,000 --> 00:01:56,039
This energetic young soldier,

20
00:01:56,440 --> 00:01:57,400
is that you?

21
00:01:57,880 --> 00:01:59,080
That was 10 years ago.

22
00:02:01,280 --> 00:02:02,760
We don't have a membership here.

23
00:02:02,760 --> 00:02:04,020
I'm changing the song.

24
00:02:04,680 --> 00:02:05,600
I was just saying,

25
00:02:05,600 --> 00:02:08,199
how could such a nice car not have a membership?

26
00:02:08,680 --> 00:02:10,280
Sit tight, we're ready to go.

27
00:02:13,000 --> 00:02:15,960
Sir, how many kilometers can this car run?

28
00:02:16,120 --> 00:02:19,079
The official standard says it can run 1146.

29
00:02:19,079 --> 00:02:20,520
1146 kilometers?

30
00:02:20,960 --> 00:02:22,490
Hey, why are you so excited?

31
00:02:23,600 --> 00:02:24,880
Sorry, sir.

32
00:02:25,280 --> 00:02:27,610
That's the total length of the Burma Road.

33
00:02:28,560 --> 00:02:29,480
The Burma Road?

34
00:02:30,320 --> 00:02:31,200
Right.

35
00:02:31,200 --> 00:02:33,260
It's the road where we ran transport.

36
00:02:35,440 --> 00:02:36,840
You're in transport too?

37
00:02:37,360 --> 00:02:38,400
Uh, no.

38
00:02:38,480 --> 00:02:40,760
Sir, he means a road from the past.

39
00:02:40,760 --> 00:02:41,560
From the past.

40
00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:47,079
That road of life and death transport

41
00:02:47,079 --> 00:02:48,940
claimed the lives of my brothers.

42
00:03:00,160 --> 00:03:02,360
Is this road still so hard to travel now?

43
00:03:05,360 --> 00:03:06,800
Is this a

44
00:03:06,800 --> 00:03:07,400
map?

45
00:03:08,120 --> 00:03:09,880
How does it move on its own?

46
00:03:09,880 --> 00:03:11,360
Did you make it move then?

47
00:03:12,880 --> 00:03:13,680
No.

48
00:03:14,400 --> 00:03:15,680
I remember

49
00:03:15,680 --> 00:03:17,880
when we just came back to run transport.

50
00:03:19,079 --> 00:03:21,280
We weren't familiar with the road conditions either.

51
00:03:21,280 --> 00:03:23,740
Sometimes when we encountered bad weather,

52
00:03:24,079 --> 00:03:25,410
our vision was blurred.

53
00:03:26,079 --> 00:03:27,810
We could only rely on our memory

54
00:03:27,960 --> 00:03:29,890
to avoid some dangerous sections.

55
00:03:30,200 --> 00:03:31,600
Like that,

56
00:03:31,600 --> 00:03:33,530
cars rolled over almost every day.

57
00:03:34,560 --> 00:03:36,560
But what we feared most was the rain.

58
00:03:37,079 --> 00:03:38,480
Not only was the road slippery,

59
00:03:38,480 --> 00:03:40,480
but we couldn't see anything at all.

60
00:03:41,480 --> 00:03:43,940
Sometimes we even had to drive with one hand,

61
00:03:44,160 --> 00:03:45,000
and use the other

62
00:03:45,000 --> 00:03:46,400
to wipe the rain outside.

63
00:03:47,000 --> 00:03:48,530
If the rain got any heavier,

64
00:03:49,079 --> 00:03:50,880
we couldn't see anything at all.

65
00:03:51,280 --> 00:03:53,280
We practically drove by intuition.

66
00:03:53,880 --> 00:03:57,280
The slightest mistake would lead to a rollover off the cliff.

67
00:04:00,680 --> 00:04:02,520
Oh, you guys are filming a movie.

68
00:04:02,920 --> 00:04:04,250
Rehearsing lines here.

69
00:04:05,400 --> 00:04:06,280
Sir,

70
00:04:06,360 --> 00:04:08,440
if I said he time-traveled here,

71
00:04:08,440 --> 00:04:09,640
would you believe it?

72
00:04:10,000 --> 00:04:12,200
I'd believe it if you could send me back.

73
00:04:13,920 --> 00:04:15,280
Speaking of transportation,

74
00:04:15,280 --> 00:04:16,200
I heard from my family

75
00:04:16,200 --> 00:04:19,880
that my great-grandfather returned from Southeast Asia to be a transporter.

76
00:04:19,880 --> 00:04:21,160
A transporter?

77
00:04:21,160 --> 00:04:21,959
Yes.

78
00:04:21,959 --> 00:04:25,280
He was quite a prominent figure among drivers back then.

79
00:04:25,560 --> 00:04:27,160
You could say he had a lot of influence.

80
00:04:27,160 --> 00:04:29,490
But then the Anti-Japanese War broke out.

81
00:04:29,800 --> 00:04:31,130
The Anti-Japanese War?

82
00:04:31,480 --> 00:04:32,680
Let me finish first.

83
00:04:32,680 --> 00:04:33,680
Don't interrupt.

84
00:04:34,280 --> 00:04:35,480
I heard from the older generation

85
00:04:35,480 --> 00:04:38,880
that Chen Jiageng called on overseas Chinese to return and help.

86
00:04:38,880 --> 00:04:40,720
My great-grandfather answered the call

87
00:04:40,720 --> 00:04:42,850
and came back to become a transporter.

88
00:04:42,960 --> 00:04:44,159
Chen Jiageng?

89
00:04:44,560 --> 00:04:46,200
Let me finish first.

90
00:04:47,560 --> 00:04:49,600
Was your great-grandfather also an overseas Chinese mechanic?

91
00:04:49,600 --> 00:04:51,330
Which transport team was he in?

92
00:04:52,280 --> 00:04:53,560
Sir,

93
00:04:53,560 --> 00:04:54,960
your surname is also Lin.

94
00:04:55,960 --> 00:04:57,690
Could your great-grandfather

95
00:04:59,680 --> 00:05:01,880
be Lin Yaozu?

96
00:05:02,200 --> 00:05:03,240
No.

97
00:05:03,240 --> 00:05:04,720
His name was Lin Fufa.

98
00:05:08,080 --> 00:05:09,600
Let me finish the story.

99
00:05:10,200 --> 00:05:14,080
Later, he took on a transport mission for a coworker that wasn't his.

100
00:05:14,480 --> 00:05:15,880
Coincidentally, that night

101
00:05:15,880 --> 00:05:17,880
they were hit by a Japanese air raid.

102
00:05:18,760 --> 00:05:20,040
The vehicle overturned,

103
00:05:20,040 --> 00:05:21,800
and he sacrificed his life.

104
00:05:27,200 --> 00:05:28,480
Sacrificed?

105
00:05:28,920 --> 00:05:30,520
Another Japanese air raid.

106
00:05:30,720 --> 00:05:33,280
This story sounds so familiar.

107
00:05:35,600 --> 00:05:39,260
Later, his coworker returned to Nanyang because of his injuries,

108
00:05:39,360 --> 00:05:41,760
but he could never let this go.

109
00:05:42,360 --> 00:05:44,800
He eventually asked his descendants to find my uncle,

110
00:05:44,800 --> 00:05:46,800
and that's how our family found out.

111
00:05:47,080 --> 00:05:47,880
And then?

112
00:05:48,120 --> 00:05:51,200
They asked around to find us,

113
00:05:51,200 --> 00:05:53,080
wanting to thank our family.

114
00:05:53,760 --> 00:05:55,480
They definitely should.

115
00:05:55,480 --> 00:05:56,920
It cost him his life.

116
00:05:57,720 --> 00:05:59,760
It wasn't about getting thanked.

117
00:05:59,760 --> 00:06:01,120
In those times,

118
00:06:01,120 --> 00:06:02,920
anyone would have done the same.

119
00:06:03,080 --> 00:06:05,800
Unfortunately, when our two families were ready to meet,

120
00:06:05,800 --> 00:06:08,120
his coworker passed away.

121
00:06:09,760 --> 00:06:12,080
What a bad coincidence.

122
00:06:13,280 --> 00:06:15,400
Life is full of bad coincidences.

123
00:06:17,400 --> 00:06:18,200
Yes.

124
00:06:18,680 --> 00:06:20,410
Life is just that unfortunate.

125
00:06:24,160 --> 00:06:25,480
Even at the right time,

126
00:06:25,960 --> 00:06:28,160
you can't always make your own choices.

127
00:06:29,760 --> 00:06:31,280
Maybe this is fate.

128
00:06:33,920 --> 00:06:34,560
So?

129
00:06:34,560 --> 00:06:36,200
Is this story good enough?

130
00:06:37,080 --> 00:06:39,320
Why is it always a sad story?

131
00:06:41,280 --> 00:06:44,120
Is that why you joined the army?

132
00:06:45,320 --> 00:06:47,980
Three generations of my family were in the army.

133
00:06:48,760 --> 00:06:50,120
That's impressive.

134
00:06:51,960 --> 00:06:52,960
I'm not bragging.

135
00:06:52,960 --> 00:06:54,420
Even though I've retired,

136
00:06:54,760 --> 00:06:55,680
if the country needs me,

137
00:06:55,680 --> 00:06:57,280
I'll step up.

138
00:07:51,120 --> 00:07:51,920
Wait.

139
00:07:52,880 --> 00:07:54,480
I forgot to bring something.

140
00:07:56,120 --> 00:07:56,680
What is it?

141
00:07:56,680 --> 00:07:57,740
Why so mysterious?

142
00:07:58,720 --> 00:08:00,120
It's a secret.

143
00:08:08,480 --> 00:08:11,600
Do you regret choosing to return to your country?

144
00:08:11,760 --> 00:08:12,680
Regret?

145
00:08:14,080 --> 00:08:16,360
Do I look like I regret it?

146
00:08:17,800 --> 00:08:19,680
My only regret is

147
00:08:19,680 --> 00:08:21,280
that I didn't return sooner.

148
00:08:24,200 --> 00:08:26,760
If you hadn't seen the sights you see now,

149
00:08:27,560 --> 00:08:29,090
would you be disappointed?

150
00:08:32,320 --> 00:08:33,120
Yes,

151
00:08:34,080 --> 00:08:35,120
I would regret it.

152
00:08:35,919 --> 00:08:38,580
Why didn't we fight to change all this back then?

153
00:08:47,600 --> 00:08:48,600
Pretty, isn't it?

154
00:08:49,120 --> 00:08:50,440
Where did you get it?

155
00:08:50,440 --> 00:08:52,040
I conjured it.

156
00:08:52,040 --> 00:08:53,170
It's really pretty.

157
00:08:55,280 --> 00:08:58,280
Grandpa, were you also afraid of the dark when you were little?

158
00:08:58,280 --> 00:08:59,320
Who isn't afraid of the dark?
